Sure! Below is a Java program that downloads an image from a URL, applies a simple filter (such as a grayscale filter), and saves the modified image to disk.

This program uses the `java.net` package for downloading the image and the `javax.imageio` package for handling image I/O. It also uses `javax.imageio.ImageIO` to read and write images.

```java
import java.awt.image.BufferedImage;
import java.awt.image.FilteredImageBufferedImage;
import java.io.*;
import java.net.URL;

public class ImageFilterDownloader {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String imageUrl = "https://example.com/image.jpg"; // Replace with your image URL
        String outputFilePath = "filtered_image.jpg";

        try {
            // Download the image
            BufferedImage originalImage = downloadImageFromUrl(imageUrl);
            if (originalImage == null) {
                System.out.println("Failed to download the image.");
                return;
            }

            // Apply a grayscale filter
            BufferedImage filteredImage = applyGrayscaleFilter(originalImage);

            // Save the filtered image to disk
            saveImageToFile(filteredImage, outputFilePath);

            System.out.println("Image downloaded, filtered, and saved to: " + outputFilePath);
        } catch (Exception e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }

    private static BufferedImage downloadImageFromUrl(String imageUrl) throws IOException {
        URL url = new URL(imageUrl);
        BufferedImage image = ImageIO.read(url.openStream());
        return image;
    }

    private static BufferedImage applyGrayscaleFilter(BufferedImage image) {
        int width = image.getWidth();
        int height = image.getHeight();
        BufferedImage filteredImage = new BufferedImage(width, height, BufferedImage.TYPE_INT_RGB);

        for (int y = 0; y < height; y++) {
            for (int x = 0; x < width; x++) {
                int pixel = image.getRGB(x, y);
                int r = (pixel >> 16) & 0xFF;
                int g = (pixel >> 8) & 0xFF;
                int b = pixel & 0xFF;

                int gray = (r + g + b) / 3;
                filteredImage.setRGB(x, y, (gray << 16) | (gray << 8) | gray);
            }
        }

        return filteredImage;
    }

    private static void saveImageToFile(BufferedImage image, String filePath) throws IOException {
        ImageIO.write(image, "jpg", new File(filePath));
    }
}
```

### Explanation:
- **`downloadImageFromUrl`**: Downloads the image from the given URL.
- **`applyGrayscaleFilter`**: Converts the image to grayscale by averaging the RGB values of each pixel.
- **`saveImageToFile`**: Saves the filtered image to a file with the specified path.

### Notes:
- You can modify the filter (e.g., brightness, contrast, etc.) by changing the `applyGrayscaleFilter` method.
- Ensure that the URL you provide is accessible and points to a valid image file.
- The program uses the `BufferedImage` and `ImageIO` classes from the Java standard library.

